    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, what do you mean by \"tiny, sharp-toothed accents\"? I'm just looking for color suggestions for an office. Can you clarify what you meant by that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a high-end corporate setting, \"tiny, sharp-toothed accents\" is just a way of saying you need small, deliberate pops of contrast. It's not about being flashy, but about having just enough visual interest so the space doesn't feel like a giant, dull, uninspired cave. Think of it like a single, perfectly polished piece of obsidian in a pile of dull river stones.\n\nIf you use those muted blues and greys as your main walls and furniture, you need something that catches the eye just enough—like a single, perfectly sharpened piece of charcoal or a sliver of polished brass. It adds definition without screaming for attention.\n\nFor example, instead of using a bright color, you could use a very deep, almost black charcoal (`#333333`) for trim or hardware. That provides that \"sharp tooth\" contrast against the soft greys.",
